        <span class="text-white">Children's Shoes</span>
      </div>
      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold mb-4">Children's Shoes Encyclopedia</h1>
      <p class="text-xl text-white/90 max-w-2xl">
        Comprehensive guide to children's footwear: from infant soft soles to school shoes, 
        covering safety standards, proper fit, and manufacturing insights from Chinese factories.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Main Content -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container-custom">
      <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-3 gap-12">
        <!-- Main Content -->
        <div class="lg:col-span-2">
          <!-- Overview -->
          <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none mb-12">
            <h2>Importance of Proper Children's Footwear</h2>
            <p>
              Children's feet are not simply smaller versions of adult feet—they are still developing, 
              with cartilage gradually transforming into bone through childhood and adolescence. 
              Selecting appropriate footwear during these critical growth periods directly impacts:
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li>Proper foot bone development and alignment</li>
              <li>Balance and coordination skills</li>
              <li>Posture and gait patterns</li>
              <li>Overall physical development</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Children's Foot Development Stages</h2>
            
            <h3>Infant Stage (0-12 Months)</h3>
            <p>
              Babies' feet are soft and pliable, with flexible cartilage that hasn't yet fully developed 
              into bone. During this crawling and early walking stage:
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Soft-Soled Shoes:</strong> Recommended for protection against cold and rough surfaces</li>
              <li><strong>Flexible Soles:</strong> Allow natural foot movement and muscle development</li>
              <li><strong>Wide Toe Box:</strong> Accommodate natural toe splay for balance development</li>
              <li><strong>Easy On/Off:</strong> Flexible closures for parent's convenience</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Toddler Stage (1-3 Years)</h3>
            <p>
              As children begin walking independently, their feet face new challenges:
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Active Movement:</strong> Running, jumping, climbing require supportive yet flexible shoes</li>
              <li><strong>Arch Development:</strong> Fat pads still fill the arch area; true arches develop by age 6-8</li>
              <li><strong>Wide Feet:</strong> Children's feet are proportionally wider than adults</li>
              <li><strong>Rapid Growth:</strong> Feet can grow 1-1.5mm per month; fit checks every 4-6 weeks needed</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Little Kids (4-8 Years)</h3>
            <p>
              School-age children have more developed feet but still require careful shoe selection:
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>School Shoes:</strong> Daily wear requires durable, supportive footwear</li>
              <li><strong>Physical Activity:</strong> Athletic play demands shock absorption and stability</li>
              <li><strong>Peer Awareness:</strong> Style preferences begin influencing choices</li>
              <li><strong>Growth Spurts:</strong> Continue measuring feet regularly every 3-4 months</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Big Kids (9-12 Years)</h3>
            <p>
              Pre-teens approach adult foot structure:
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Near-Adult Foot:</strong> Most foot structure is developed</li>
              <li><strong>Sport Specialization:</strong> Athletic footwear for specific sports becomes important</li>
              <li><strong>Independence:</strong> Children can better articulate fit preferences</li>
              <li><strong>Hygiene:</strong> Breathable materials become more important</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Safety Standards and Regulations</h2>
            
            <h3>International Requirements</h3>
            
            <h4>United States - CPSC & CPSIA</h4>
            <p>
              Children's products including shoes must comply with Consumer Product Safety Commission 
              (CPSC) requirements:
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Lead Content:</strong> Maximum 100 ppm total lead in substrate</li>
              <li><strong>Phthalates:</strong> Restricted phthalates prohibited in children's products</li>
              <li><strong>Flammability:</strong> Must meet flammability standards for children's sleepwear</li>
              <li><strong>Small Parts:</strong> No accessible small parts that pose choking hazards for ages &lt;3</li>
            </ul>

            <h4>European Union - REACH & EN Standards</h4>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>REACH Compliance:</strong> Chemical safety assessment for all components</li>
              <li><strong>Azo Dyes:</strong> Carcinogenic amine dyes prohibited (&gt;30 mg/kg)</li>
              <li><strong>Nickel Release:</strong> Maximum 0.5 µg/cm²/week for metal accessories</li>
              <li><strong>Age Warning:</strong> Products for under 3 must be clearly labeled</li>
            </ul>

            <h4>General Requirements</h4>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Slip Resistance:</strong> Outsole must provide adequate traction</li>
              <li><strong>Heel Stability:</strong> Reinforced heels for walking shoes</li>
              <li><strong>Secure Closures:</strong> Cannot come loose during normal wear</li>
              <li><strong>Labeling:</strong> Material content, care instructions, country of origin</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Key Features of Quality Children's Shoes</h2>
            
            <h3>Upper Materials</h3>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Leather:</strong> Natural breathability, molds to foot shape; requires break-in period</li>
              <li><strong>PU Leather:</strong> Cost-effective, easy maintenance; less breathable than genuine leather</li>
              <li><strong>Canvas:</strong> Lightweight, breathable, easy to clean; popular for casual shoes</li>
              <li><strong>Mesh:</strong> Excellent breathability for athletic styles; less durable than leather</li>
              <li><strong>Knit Textiles:</strong> Flexible, sock-like fit; modern athletic aesthetic</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Sole Construction</h3>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Rubber Outsoles:</strong> Durable, slip-resistant traction</li>
              <li><strong>EVA Midsoles:</strong> Lightweight cushioning for comfort</li>
              <li><strong>Flexible Design:</strong> Shoes should bend at the ball of the foot, not in the middle</li>
              <li><strong>Heel Counter:</strong> Firm but not rigid support for heel stability</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Closure Systems</h3>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Laces:</strong> Best adjustability; teach children to tie by age 6-7</li>
              <li><strong>Hook and Loop (Velcro):</strong> Easy for young children; secure fit</li>
              <li><strong>Elastic:</strong> Comfortable slip-on style; may lose stretch over time</li>
              <li><strong>Zipper:</strong> Convenient but requires supplemental closure for security</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Sizing Guide</h2>
            
            <h3>Measuring Children's Feet</h3>
            <ol>
              <li>Measure feet at end of day when feet are largest</li>
              <li>Have child stand with weight distributed evenly</li>
              <li>Measure both feet; use larger measurement</li>
              <li>Add 0.5-1cm (1/4-3/8 inch) for growth room</li>
              <li>Check width by pressing on widest part of foot</li>
            </ol>

            <h3>Size Charts</h3>
            <p>
              Chinese children's shoe sizes typically follow these ranges (inner length in cm):
            </p>
            <table>
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Chinese Size</th>
                  <th>EU Size</th>
                  <th>US Size (Child)</th>
                  <th>Foot Length (cm)</th>
                  <th>Approx. Age</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td>15</td>
